➡️Types of NSAIDs 
Ibuprofen (Advil, Motrin, Midol) 
Naproxen (Aleve, Naprosyn) 
Identify the onset. For example, the onset of action of Advil is 30 min with an elimination half-life of 2–4 h

From Chew sticks to High-Tech Here's the history of the 🪥

The toothbrush has a long and fascinating history, dating back thousands of years. 
While the modern toothbrush as we know it today was invented in the 1930s, people have been using various tools to clean their teeth for millennia.

The earliest known toothbrush was a chew stick, which was a thin twig with a frayed end that people would rub against their teeth to remove plaque and food particles. This practice dates back as far as 3000 BCE in ancient Babylon and Egypt.

In ancient China, around 1600 BCE, people used something called a "chewing stick," which was made from aromatic tree twigs to freshen their breath and clean their teeth.

The first bristle toothbrush, similar to what we use today, was invented in China during the Tang Dynasty in the 7th century. 
These early toothbrushes were made of bamboo 🎋or animal bone, with bristles made from the hairs of pigs, horses, or badgers. 

The use of toothbrushes spread to Europe in the 17th century, where the bristles were made from horsehair or feathers🪶

It wasn't until the 1930s that the modern toothbrush, with synthetic bristles and a plastic handle, was invented.

Today, there are many different types of toothbrushes available, including electric toothbrushes, soft-bristled toothbrushes, and even toothbrushes with built-in timers to help people brush for the recommended two minutes. 

The toothbrush remains an essential tool for maintaining good oral hygiene and overall health.

Let’s talk about RMGI:
Resin-modified glass ionomer (RMGI) is a type of material that combines the properties of glass ionomer and resin-based materials. It is made by mixing a powder of glass particles with an aqueous solution of an acid, which produces an ionomer “cement.” Resin is then added to the mixture to improve its mechanical properties and bond strength.

RMGI has the ability to bond chemically to the tooth structure and release fluoride, which helps to prevent tooth decay. It also has decent aesthetic properties and can be used on anterior teeth. RMGI proper is used for a variety of dental restorations such as fillings, crowns, and bridges but in this case, we are using Vanish XT, which is a temporary material primarily used in the hands of preventatively focused clinicians (like me.)

Is a 11/12 too big to insert on an anterior tooth?

Subgingival scaling is a critical aspect of periodontal care even on little teeth. Here are some tips to help with the insertion of a 11/12 in tough areas

1️⃣ Master Your Instrument Grip
Learn how to hold the 11/12 Gracey instrument with precision and comfort, ensuring optimal control and maneuverability during the scaling process. In some areas, the instrument will be held between the 2nd and 3rd knuckle while perky on the fulcrum and in others it’ll rest in the crook of your hand. Look at both these options while placing your fulcrum to keep your wrist neutral. 

2️⃣ Establish a Stable Fulcrum
Discover the correct placement of your fulcrum on the tooth, providing stability and control while minimizing patient discomfort. In most cases you will be 1-2 teeth away and in some instances, you may be the fulcrum on the same tooth and leaning the fulcrum finger to insert. Don’t be afraid to get close. 

3️⃣ Position the Instrument Tip at the Gum Line
Understand the importance of placing the toe of the instrument at the gum line, ensuring proper insertion and access to the subgingival area. Lean the face into the tooth to close it and slid the toe 3rd sub. 

4️⃣ Gentle Push Underneath the Gum
Master the technique of gently pushing the instrument underneath the gum, ensuring the effective removal of calculus and plaque from the subgingival surfaces. Once you’ve closed to insert you need to reopen to the correct angulation in order to activate. Often the terminal shank is a good gauge, look for it to be parallel to the tooth. 

5️⃣ Skillful Scaling
Scale with control and intention, utilizing controlled and precise movements to remove deposits while minimizing trauma to the surrounding tissues. Leading your scaling with the toe 3rd with small oblique and vertical strokes. Now getting into the interproximal requires some serious rolling but not too much rolling! We’ll save that one for next time.

I'm not a mechanical engineer, but I know my way around a mechanical room.

Let's take a step back to better understand what  "backflow" is, where it comes from, and whether all dental offices experience this? 

SCIENCE: Backflow is the unwanted reversal of water flow within a plumbing system, where water, saliva, blood and all those microbes from within your suction lines and pipes flow back into the water supply instead of moving in their intended direction (out and into your traps, amalgam separator, compressor and sewer. This goes as far back in your waterlines as the master sewer or drains that empty out your entire dental office, and most offices have a backflow preventer valve at that source. The struggle we have is not always that deep into the evacuation system but closer to the source; your suction lines are the most vulnerable areas.
HOW THEY WORK: Backflow preventors have a valve built in that blocks fluid and debris from returning into the lines in moments of pressure loss. Your dental chair may have this but often the concern is directly at the suction source. 
SOLUTION: Safe-Flo™ Saliva Ejectors by HuFriedyGroup have a built in valve that closes when pressure is lost. This is a great disposable option for additional piece of mind and protects patients from the change of backflow that happens in 1 in 5 patients. 
Backflow prevention devices are used to safeguard the water supply and prevent such occurrences and in many instances, are mandatory.
Do this to minimize the risk:
1. Installing backflow prevention devices, like air gaps or appropriate backflow preventers, in their waterlines or attached to the dental units.
2. Regularly maintaining and testing backflow prevention equipment.
3. Educating team and not allowing patients to close their mouths on the suction or letting the suction completely attach to soft tissue. 
4. Use sterile, single-use water items for dental procedures.
5. Monitoring water pressure.
6. Use Safe-Flo™ Saliva Ejectors and Valves by @hufriedygroup to be extra confident. They are easily attached to your saliva ejector and disposable for peace of mind. 
7. Test your waterlines for pathogens using waterline test kits offered.

Hold my HVE; here’s how backflow happens. I’m not a mechanical engineer, but I hired one when I built my office, and he taught me a few things about the flow/safeguards and what’s up to building code standards. 
Yes, we’ve seen the “don’t close on the suction” posts; there’s a little more to it than that. 

Usually, this can happen because of drops or spikes in pressure frequently across the entire office or the building your practice is in. Power fluctuations can also change pressure. 
A dental office and building have a backflow preventer at the end of the line between your drain/sewer and main lines, but the most challenging place to regulate is chairside.

What’s the perfect magnification for loupes? 
Big ask- comment below with your magnification so the world can decide. Often I’m asked what mag is the right mag… share your details/compare to mine. 

Selecting the perfect magnification can seem daunting at times, how much is too much or not enough if you’ve NEVER worn loupes before? 

This is a pivotal decision for your practice and can significantly impact your clinical performance. 

Consider several key factors to make an informed choice that aligns with your professional needs and enhances patient care. Here is what led me to work with 4x loupes and the transitions I made from my first pair. 

Do hygienists need higher magnification? 
Not specifically- we usually live in the 2.5-3.5x zone. 
When doing hygiene, this will show most of the arch. More than a quadrant. 

Who wants higher magnification? Usually, Dentists, Restorative Hygienists, Therapists and anyone doing procedures on one tooth for extended periods of time. 

🦷You’re working on something very specific. 
🦷You don’t move around too much. 

Here’s my history: 
2007-2012 - No loupes (big regrets) 
2013 My first pair was 1.5x 
2019 Second pair was 2.5 
2021 Third pair 3.5x 
2023 now I have 4x 

I switch between mine based on the day and the procedure I’m doing. 

Assess your practice requirements and consider a magnification level that allows you to comfortably visualize intricate details without sacrificing your field of view. 

Strike a balance between enhanced detail and maintaining a clear overview of the treatment area specific to the procedure you often perform the most.

Here are a few seemingly simple but very critical steps you want to take advantage of when using LIQUIDAM Isolation for your Zoom whitening patients. 

1. Avoid Flavours: Removing biofilm is important when polishing anything with a flavour. Yummy prophy pastes kickstart the salivary glands. Additionally it has oils, fluoride and other ingredients that may interfere with the Liquidam. Best to avoid and opt for a plain pumice. 
2. Gauze: The vestibular gauze roll is important but can be too big for people with thin vestibules or tight frenums. If you can't fit the roll in, take a piece of 2X2 (or two.) Open it halfway and tightly roll it into a sausage. Use that instead and pack it in deep.
3. Dry Isolation first: Pack all your gauze in first before applying the liquid dam. It'll absorb moisture and slow down salivary flow. It also locks the Liquidam in place. 
4. Dry=Good- In restorative, we avoid desiccating soft and hard tissue; in this case, dry is good. Use your Air/water syringe to dry each section before adding your first layer of Liquidam. Do the gingival margin first before moving on and dry in between. 
5. Use your mirror- Indirect vision in the posteriors is the key. Follow the "NO PINK" rule throughout the entire mouth and both arches. NO soft tissue should be visible. This includes attached and free and attached gingiva, cheeks, and lips; the tongue should be back and behind the barrier built into the retractor.

Carbamide Peroxide 10%, 16%, 22% vs Hydrogen Peroxide 6% and 9.5%
Choosing between hydrogen Peroxide and carbamide Peroxide largely depends on the patient's goals and their tolerance for sensitivity during teeth whitening.

1. Whitening Speed: Hydrogen Peroxide is ideal when quick results are a priority, delivering significant whitening within the first hour. It suits those seeking immediate improvements.

2. Treatment Duration: Carbamide Peroxide offers a gradual whitening process, with half of its effect occurring in the first 2 hours and the remainder over the next 6 hours. It's suitable for patients who prefer a more extended, less intense whitening experience.

3. Sensitivity Considerations: Hydrogen Peroxide can cause more immediate sensitivity, while Carbamide Peroxide may lead to milder immediate sensitivity. 
Tailor the choice to the patient's sensitivity profile and desired duration of discomfort.

What’s the difference between Hydrogen Peroxide and Carbamide Peroxide? 

The main difference between Hydrogen Peroxide (HP) and Carbamide Peroxide (CP) is that HP is an effective whitening agent by itself. On the other hand, CP contains hydrogen Peroxide in it. For every 30% of Carbamide Peroxide, there is also 10% of Hydrogen Peroxide.

Hydrogen Peroxide and Carbamide Peroxide differ primarily in their composition and speed of action. Hydrogen Peroxide is a standalone whitening agent known for its rapid reactivity, breaking down stains swiftly within 30 to 60 minutes. In contrast, Carbamide Peroxide comprises both Hydrogen Peroxide and urea, and it acts more gradually, releasing half of its whitening power during the first 2 hours and the remainder over the next 6 hours.

While both Peroxides share similarities as oxidizing agents, effective teeth whiteners, and potential sources of sensitivity, it’s essential to weigh the variations in composition and speed when choosing the most suitable whitening agent for specific patient needs and preferences. Common seemingly innocent mistakes students and seasoned clinicians make with a 204S:
(Myself included) 

Comment Scaler below and I’ll send you the full @hufriedygroup catalog (all 300+ pages of ✨ magical instruments) 

TOO OPEN- Over-opening creates adaptation issues rolling the instrument on the back and not allowing the cutting edge to adapt to the surface. This can cause burnished calculus and is unsafe as the clinician may slip on the back or not sharp part of the instrument.

TOO CLOSED- Over-closing creates a “”face-to-tooth”” problem, the face or top of the instrument is closed to the tooth and doesn’t allow the cutting edge to remove deposits.

TERMINAL SHANK IN THE WAY- Not opening enough may cause the terminal shank to hit the incisal edge of the tooth. Focus on leaving a little space between the terminal shank and the tooth, as close to parallel as possible.

OVER ROLLING- This sickle scaler is pointy at the end so rolling is subtle to allow for adaptation to the tip 3rd of the instrument. If you over-roll, you’ll know (and so will the patient.)

FINGER ACTIVATION- Give your fingers a rest, try activating from the wrist more. This provided more stability in the strokes and gives consistency when transitioning from vertical to oblique strokes between the line angles.

Dull and worn instruments increase the chance of burnished calc, patient discomfort and clinician strained hands, wrists and necks! 
Work smarter not harder peeps.

Pre-whitening protocol to prevent sensitivity:
Don’t be reactive, be PROactive to prevent sensitivity.
Save this post for later to follow along with pre-whitening steps to prevent sensitivity with your patients prior to any whitening treatment.
1. Ensure your patient doesn’t have active untreated decay by taking anterior PA’s and posterior bitewings.
2. Start patients on desensitizing agents ideally 2 weeks before whitening. (Things like toothpaste with Potassium Nitrate or Novamin can assist wonderfully with sensitivity prevention!)
3. Make custom trays in advance and provide patients with Relief ACP Gel prior to their treatment. Have the patient come to the office with the trays in with the gel on for at least 30 minutes before. The Amorphous Calcium Phosphate blocks the tubules but doesn’t affect the whitening outcome.
4. If not contraindicated by your patients health history, recommend the patient take Ibuprofin 30 minutes prior, with the review of the DDS/DMD as the prescriber.

Whitening patients should avoid using Stannous Fluoride while whitening:
1. It can block the tubules and can interfere with the results
2. Some can stain teeth

*Always consult with your Doc’s and consider medical history for all recommendations.
